{"cursor":"23514","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"'Circular dichroism (CD)' refers to the differential absorption of left and\nright circularly polarized light. This phenomenon was discovered by Jean-Baptiste Biot,\nAugustin Fresnel, and AimÃ© Cotton in the first half of the 19th\ncentury. It is exhibited in the absorption bands of optically active\nchiral molecules. CD spectroscopy has a wide range of applications in many\ndifferent fields. Most notably, UV CD is used to investigate the secondary\nstructure of proteins. UV/Vis CD is used to investigate charge-\ntransfer transitions. Near-infrared CD is used to investigate\ngeometric and electronic structure by probing metal dâd transitions. Vibrational circular\ndichroism, which uses light from the infrared energy region, is used for\nstructural studies of small organic molecules, and most recently proteins and\nDNA.\n","linknr":363,"url":"Circular_dichroism","recorded":1362509642,"links":31,"instances":["mathematics","waves","physics","electromagnetic_radiation","geometry","chemistry"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Polarization","Physical quantities","Protein structure"],"headings":["Physical principles","Application to biological molecules","Experimental limitations","See also","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/5/5e/Linearly_pol.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/4/4b/Circularly_pol.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/5/e/9/5e9f87f0cfa80f3b5a4beac70ea61afa.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/b/c/f/bcf0405da74863a01dd3f75e031c2a7f.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/b/b/d/bbdd19510aeda17eb7653d54c38028dc.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/f/0/e/f0ea7df646925a94d6c39f066855d6f5.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/1/c/6/1c652a004d54410f13b4a13a1a102ac8.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/4/9/849f9df2d516521b9163ae28c1fbc16a.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/b/3/d/b3d306c74d1ca0a424841b3362d32361.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/2/8/4/28437747d1349be29dba770931